  <thing id="fBlendCrm" name="Blend Cream" description="This pale gray cream dulls the color of flesh, fur, scales, and hair. It allows those affected to better blend in with background and shadow, making it easier to hide.\n\nApplying Blend Cream is a standard action that provokes attacks of opportunity. Blend cream provides a +1 alchemical bonus on Hide checks for 1 hour. This substance gives no ability to hide in plain sight or without sufficient cover.\n\nIt can be made with a DC 20 Craft (Alchemy) check.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" summary="+1 Alch bonus to Hide for 1 hour" stacking="merge">
    <comment>Complete Adventurer, Chapter 4, Page 118</comment>
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="50"/>
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="1"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="SpecSubs" name="Special Substances" abbrev="Substances"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fCandleFoc" name="Candle, focusing" description="This large green taper burns quickly, lasting only 1 hour despite it&apos;s size. While burning, a focusing candle fills the air with a fresh, crisp odor. The candle is a great boon to those within 20 feet who are engaged in strenuous mental activity. It grants a +1 circumstance bonus on Appraise, Decipher Script, Forgery, and Search checks. When making a skill check that takes more than one action to complete (such as Decipher Script), characters gain the bonus only if they spend the entire duration of the check within 20 feet of the candle.\n\nIt can be made with a DC 25 Craft (Alchemy) check.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" summary="+1 Alch bonus to Appraise, Decipher Script, Forgery, and Search for 1 hour" stacking="merge">
    <comment>Complete Adventurer, Chapter 4, Page 118</comment>
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="100"/>
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="1"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="SpecSubs" name="Special Substances" abbrev="Substances"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fCatstink" name="Catstink" description="A dose of this alchemical compound sprinkled on your trail temporarily confuses the scent ability of any creature. \n\nAny creature using scent to track you must succeed on a DC 15 Survival check or lose your trail. If the trail is lost, the creature can attempt to relocate it using the normal rules for the Track feat, but the check DC is increased by 2. The odor of Catstink remains in effect for 10 minutes after the substance is used. Sprinkling Catstink on one&apos;s trail is a standard action that provokes attacks of opportunity.\n\nIt can be made with a DC 20 Craft (Alchemy) check.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" summary="Creatures tracking by scent make DC15 Survival or lose trail, harder to regain trail" stacking="merge">
    <comment>Complete Adventurer, Chapter 4, Page 118</comment>
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="50"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="SpecSubs" name="Special Substances" abbrev="Substances"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fFareyeOil" name="Fareye Oil" description="When applied to the eyes, this clear oil sharpens the user&apos;s vision for a short time, providing a +1 alchemical bonus on Spot checks for 1 minute.\n\nOne dose of fareye oil is enough to affect the eyes of a creature of any size, but the creature must have eyes to gain any benefit from the oil. Applying fareye oil  is a standard action that provokes attacks of opportunity.\n\nIt can be made with a DC 20 Craft (Alchemy) check.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" summary="+1 Alch bonus to Spot for 1 min" stacking="merge">
    <comment>Complete Adventurer, Chapter 4, Page 118</comment>
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="25"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="SpecSubs" name="Special Substances" abbrev="Substances"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fFlashPell" name="Flash Pellet" description="This tiny brittle object is often disguised as a button or other decoration. You can throw a flash pellet as a ranged attack with a range increment of 5 feet. When thrown against a hard surface, it bursts with a bright flash of light. All creatures within a 5 foot radius burst must succeed on a DC 15 Fort save or be blinded for 1 round and dazzled for 1 round after that.\n\nIt can be made with a DC 25 Craft (Alchemy) check.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" summary="Ranged attack, those in 5 ft radius burst, DC 15 Fort or blind 1 rd, then dazed 1 rd" stacking="merge">
    <comment>Complete Adventurer, Chapter 4, Page 118</comment>
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="50"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="SpecSubs" name="Special Substances" abbrev="Substances"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fFreeglide" name="Freeglide" description="This greenish grey gel can be applied to a creature&apos;s hide, hair, clothing, or armor. The gel makes the affected surface slippery and hard to grab or hold, providing a +1 alchemical bonus on Escape Artist checks for 1 hour.\n\nOne dose is enough to coat a single medium creature, and applying the oil is a standard action that provokes attacks of opportunity. If it is applied to clothing or armor, the benefits are lost if the garments are removed. Likewise, if applied to the skin, the benefit is lost when clothing or armor is donned.\n\nIt can be made with a DC 20 Craft (Alchemy) check.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" summary="+1 Alch bonus to Escape Artist for 1 hour" stacking="merge">
    <comment>Complete Adventurer, Chapter 4, Page 118</comment>
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="20"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="SpecSubs" name="Special Substances" abbrev="Substances"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fHawkOint" name="Hawk&apos;s Ointment" description="This thick, acidic gel temporarily sharpens the user&apos;s vision, granting a +1 bonus on Search and Spot checks for 2 minutes. Once its beneficial effects have worn off, the gel burns and stings, imposing a -2 penalty to those skills for 10 minutes. Characters can halve the remaining duration of the penalty by spending a round washing out thier eyes with clean water.\n\nApplying the ointment or washing out one&apos;s eyes are full round actions that provoke attacks of opportunity.\n\nIt can be made with a DC 25 Craft (Alchemy) check.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" summary="+1 Alch bonus to Spot and Search 2 min, then -2 penalty for 10 min" stacking="merge">
    <comment>Complete Adventurer, Chapter 4, Page 118</comment>
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="50"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="SpecSubs" name="Special Substances" abbrev="Substances"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fHealBalm" name="Healer&apos;s Balm" description="This smooth, sweet smelling balm allows the healer to better sooth the effects of wounds, disease, and poison. Healer&apos;s balm provides a +1 alchemical bonus to Heal checks made to help an affected creature. The effect lasts 1 minute.\n\nOne dose is enough to coat a single medium creature. Applying the balm is a standard action that provokes attacks of opportunity. It can be applied as part of a standard action made to administer first aid, treat a wound, or treat poison.\n\nIt can be made with a DC 20 Craft (Alchemy) check.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" summary="+1 Alch bonus to Heal for 1 min, may be applied as part of other checks" stacking="merge">
    <comment>Complete Adventurer, Chapter 4, Page 118</comment>
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="10"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="SpecSubs" name="Special Substances" abbrev="Substances"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fKeenearP" name="Keenear Powder" description="This dry, white powder sharpens acreature&apos;s hearing when applied to the ear, providing a +1 alchemical bonus on Listen checks for 1 minute. It is more often used by those trying to avoid prowling guards than those tasked with guarding an area for a longer time.\n\nOne dose of keenear powder is enough to affect the ears of a creature of any size, but the creature must have ears to gain any benefit from the powder. Applying keenear powder  is a standard action that provokes attacks of opportunity.\n\nIt can be made with a DC 20 Craft (Alchemy) check.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" summary="+1 Alch bonus to Listen for 1 min" stacking="merge">
    <comment>Complete Adventurer, Chapter 4, Page 118</comment>
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="20"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="SpecSubs" name="Special Substances" abbrev="Substances"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fLockGreas" name="Lockslip Grease" description="Lockslip grease is a thick, reddish oil that loosens the mechanisms of nonmagical locks, providing a +1 alchemical bonus on Open Lock checks made against the affected lock for 1 minute.\n\nOne dose of lockslip grease is enough to affect a lock of any size, but it has no affect on magical locks. Applying lockslip grease is a standard action that provokes attacks of opportunity.\n\nIt can be made with a DC 20 Craft (Alchemy) check.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" summary="+1 Alch bonus to Open Lock for 1 min, only on non-magic locks" stacking="merge">
    <comment>Complete Adventurer, Chapter 4, Page 119</comment>
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="50"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="SpecSubs" name="Special Substances" abbrev="Substances"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fNatureDr" name="Nature&apos;s Draught" description="This substance is a murky, pungent liquid that causes subtle changes in the drinker&apos;s scent for 12 hours when drunk. Animals respond well to this scent, finding the bearer less threatening and easier to trust, granting them a +1 alchemical bonus on Handle Animcal and Wild Empathy checks for the duration.\n\nIt can be made with a DC 25 Craft (Alchemy) check.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" summary="+1 Alch bonus to Handle Animal or Wild empathy for 12 hours" stacking="merge">
    <comment>Complete Adventurer, Chapter 4, Page 119</comment>
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="50"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="SpecSubs" name="Special Substances" abbrev="Substances"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fSoftfoot" name="Softfoot" description="Softfoot is a fine gray powder that muffles sound when applied to the bottom of a foot or boot, granting a +1 alchemical bonus to Move Silently checks for 1 hour.\n\nOne dose is enough to affect one medium creature with 1 pair of feet. Each additional pair of feet requires an additional dose. Applying softfoot is a standard action that provokes attacks of opportunity. If applied to footwear, the benefit is lost when the footwear is removed, and if applied directly to feet, the bonus is lost once shoes are donned\n\nIt can be made with a DC 20 Craft (Alchemy) check.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" summary="+1 Alch bonus to Move Silently for 1 hour" stacking="merge">
    <comment>Complete Adventurer, Chapter 4, Page 119</comment>
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="50"/>
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="1"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="SpecSubs" name="Special Substances" abbrev="Substances"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fSuregrip" name="Suregrip" description="This thick white paste, when applied to the hands and feet, strengthens and steadies the user&apos;s grip, granting a +1 alchemical bonus on Climb checks for 1 minute.\n\nOne dose is enough to affect the hands and feet of one medium creature. Applying suregrip is a standard action that provokes attacks of opportunity. \n\nIt can be made with a DC 20 Craft (Alchemy) check.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" summary="+1 Alch bonus to Climb for 1 min" stacking="merge">
    <comment>Complete Adventurer, Chapter 4, Page 119</comment>
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="20"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="SpecSubs" name="Special Substances" abbrev="Substances"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fCapRetain" name="Capsule Retainer" description="A capsule retainer consists of a rubbery strap looped inside the teeth and fitted with a small metal ring that can hold one alchemical capsule.\n\nFitting a capsule into an empty retainer is a full round action that provokes attacks of opportunity. Using a capsule already equipped is a swift action that does not provoke attacks of opportunity.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="100"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="thing" tag="holder" name="Holder" abbrev="???"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="Clothing"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fAlchTooth" name="Alchemical Tooth" description="As its name suggests, this specially concealed item has been made to look like a tooth. It functions in all ways as a capsule retainer, but is very hard to find without a thorough search (Search DC30). \n\nRather than keeping alchemical capsules, some extremely dedicated spies fill thiers with a single dose of contact or ingested poison to avoid capture while alive. There is no way to affect another target with the poison as part or a bite attack.\n\nFitting a capsule into an empty alchemical tooth is a full round action that provokes attacks of opportunity. Using a capsule already equipped is a swift action that does not provoke attacks of opportunity.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="300"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="thing" tag="holder" name="Holder" abbrev="???"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="Clothing"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fAntitoCap" name="Antitoxin Capsule" description="This capsule holds a dose of weak antitoxin, granting a +1 alchemical bonus on Fort saves made against poison for 1 minute.\n\nIt can be made with a DC 20 Craft (Alchemy) check.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="15"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="SpecSubs" name="Special Substances" abbrev="Substances"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fIronMnCap" name="Ironman Capsule" description="This capsule holds a dose of thick, pale liquid allowing the imbiber to ignore pain and distraction. Anyone using the capsule while staggered can ignore the restrictions on the number of actions they can take in that round. They may do a standard and a move, 2 moves, or a full round action. The affect ends immediately after the round&apos;s actions are finished.\n\nAn ironman capsule does not prevent a character from losing a hit point if he is already at or below 0 hit points, and does not prevent the user from dieing when he reaches -10.\n\nIt can be made with a DC 20 Craft (Alchemy) check.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="15"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="SpecSubs" name="Special Substances" abbrev="Substances"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fLeapCap" name="Leap Capsule" description="The thick gray liquid in this capsule allows the user to make powerful leaps for a short time. The user gains a +4 alchemical bonus on Jump checks for 1 round. The affect ends immediately after the round&apos;s actions are finished.\n\nIt can be made with a DC 25 Craft (Alchemy) check.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="15"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="SpecSubs" name="Special Substances" abbrev="Substances"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fStableCap" name="Stability Capsule" description="The thick blue liquid in this capsule heightens the user&apos;s sense of balance for a short while. The user gains a +4 alchemical bonus on Balance checks for 1 round. The affect ends immediately after the round&apos;s actions are finished.\n\nIt can be made with a DC 20 Craft (Alchemy) check.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="15"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="SpecSubs" name="Special Substances" abbrev="Substances"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fStrArmCap" name="Strongarm Capsule" description="The thin red liquid in this capsule provides a temporary boost to physical power, resulting in a +1 alchemical bonus on Str checks and melee weapon damage for 2 rounds. Once the duration is up, the user becomes fatigued, or exhausted if he was already fatigued.\n\nIt can be made with a DC 35 Craft (Alchemy) check.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="125"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="SpecSubs" name="Special Substances" abbrev="Substances"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fSwiftSCap" name="Swiftstride Capsule" description="The thin blue liquid in this capsule provides a temporary boost to speed, increasing the user&apos;s base land speed by 5 feet for 2 rounds. Once the duration is up, the user becomes fatigued, or exhausted if he was already fatigued.\n\nIt can be made with a DC 35 Craft (Alchemy) check.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="15"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="SpecSubs" name="Special Substances" abbrev="Substances"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fWeapCapRe" name="Weapon Capsule Retainer" description="A capsule retainer consists of a long leather thong that is wrapped around a melee or thrown (not projectile) weapon just at the base of the blade or striking surface and holds a thin, fitted metal ring that can hold one alchemical capsule.\n\nOnly one weapon capsule retainer can be attached to a weapon, and attaching it to the weapon or fitting a capsule into an empty retainer is a full round action that provokes attacks of opportunity. Using a capsule already equipped is a swift action that does not provoke attacks of opportunity.\n\nAlchemical weapon capsules can also be filled with a single dose of any injury poison, allowing the wielder to poison his enemies. A character using poison in this way still faces all the normal risks of using poison (including accidental exposure when activating the capsule or with a natural 1 on any attack roll).\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="100"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="thing" tag="holder" name="Holder" abbrev="???"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="Clothing"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="f3WeapCapR" name="Weapon Capsule Retainer, Triple" description="A triple capsule retainer consists of a long leather thong that is wrapped around a melee or thrown (not projectile) weapon just at the base of the blade or striking surface and holds three thin, fitted metal ring that can each hold one alchemical capsule.\n\nOnly one triple weapon capsule retainer can be attached to a weapon, and attaching it to the weapon or fitting a capsule into an empty retainer is a full round action that provokes attacks of opportunity (thus filling all 3 slots with capsules takes 3 full round actions). A character using a triple weapon capsule retainer can use one, two, or all three attached capsules as part of the same swift action that does not provoke attacks of opportunity.\n\nAlchemical weapon capsules can also be filled with a single dose of any injury poison, allowing the wielder to poison his enemies. A character using poison in this way still faces all the normal risks of using poison (including accidental exposure when activating the capsule or with a natural 1 on any attack roll).\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="450"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="thing" tag="holder" name="Holder" abbrev="???"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="Clothing"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fGhostBli" name="Ghostblight" description="A ghostblight alchemical capsule coats a melee or thrown weapon with a thick gray liquid. This substance allows the weapon to ignore the normal miss chance that applies when striking incorporeal creatures (as though the weapon had the ghost touch magical property). \n\nThe capsule&apos;s effect lasts for 3 rounds.\n\nIt can be made with a DC 35 Craft (Alchemy) check.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="100"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="SpecSubs"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fQuickFlam" name="Quickflame Weapon Capsule" description="A quickflame alchemical capsule coats a melee or thrown weapon with a thin sheet of oil that instantly bursts into flame. This substance allows the weapon to deal extra fire damage without harming the weapon or wielder. A weapon treated with quickflame deals 1d6 points of fire damage with each successful strike. This fire damage does not stack with any fire damage the weapon already deals.\n\nThe capsule&apos;s effect lasts for 1 round, ending at the start of the wielders next turn.\n\nIt can be made with a DC 25 Craft (Alchemy) check.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="25"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="SpecSubs"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fQuickFrst" name="Quickfrost Weapon Capsule" description="A quickfrost alchemical capsule coats a melee or thrown weapon with a thin sheet of oil that instantly cools to a dangerously low temperature. This substance allows the weapon to deal extra cold damage without harming the weapon or wielder. A weapon treated with quickfrost deals 1d6 points of cold damage with each successful strike. This cold damage does not stack with any cold damage the weapon already deals.\n\nThe capsule&apos;s effect lasts for 1 round, ending at the start of the wielders next turn.\n\nIt can be made with a DC 25 Craft (Alchemy) check.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="25"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="SpecSubs"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fQuickSprk" name="Quickspark Weapon Capsule" description="A quickspark alchemical capsule coats a melee or thrown weapon with a thin sheet of oil that crackles and sparks with electrical energy. This substance allows the weapon to deal extra electricity damage without harming the weapon or wielder. A weapon treated with quickspark deals 1d6 points of electricity damage with each successful strike. This electricity damage does not stack with any electricity damage the weapon already deals.\n\nThe capsule&apos;s effect lasts for 1 round, ending at the start of the wielders next turn.\n\nIt can be made with a DC 25 Craft (Alchemy) check.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="25"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="SpecSubs"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fQuickSilv" name="Quicksilver Weapon Capsule" description="A quicksilver alchemical capsule coats a melee or thrown weapon with a thick, silvery liquid. This substance allows the weapon to deal damage as though the weapon were coated with silver (including the normal -1 penalty on damage for silvered weapons). \n\nThe capsule&apos;s effect lasts for 3 rounds and override any other special material effects on the weapon.\n\nIt can be made with a DC 30 Craft (Alchemy) check.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="50"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="SpecSubs"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fAnTrainK" name="Animal Training Kit" description="This kit includes signal whistles, a short hollow pole with a loop of rope threaded through it, savory treats, and other well made items suited for the training of animals.\n\nThis kit grants a +2 circumstance bonus on Handle Animal checks made for teaching animals tricks, training animals for a purpose, or rearing a wild animal. It does not grant a bonus for other uses of the Handle Animal skill.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="75"/>
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="15"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="Tools"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fBalPole" name="Balance Pole" description="This long, flexible pole is the perfect tool for balancing. The pole is 10 feet long, so it cannot be used in any space that allows less than 5 feet of clearance on either side. Provided the user has space to employ the pole properly, it grants a +2 circumstance bonus on Balance checks.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="5"/>
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="5"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="Tools"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fCamoKit" name="Camouflage Kit" description="This bag contains face paints, dyes, colored cloth, and other accessories appropriate for creating a camouflaged appearance. The kit is the perfect tool for hiding and provides a +2 circumstance bonus on Hide checks. Gaining this benefit requires 1 minute of work. A camouflage kit is exhausted after 10 uses.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="40"/>
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="5"/>
    <fieldval field="hTotal" value="10"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="ShowCharge"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="Tools"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fForgeKit" name="Forgery Kit" description="This small case holds a broad selection of paper types, pens, and several colors of ink. In addition, the kit contains samples of prominent family and national crests and the like. This kit is the perfect tool for attempting a forgery and grants a +2 circumstance bonus on Forgery checks. A forgery kit is exhausted after 10 uses.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="40"/>
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="5"/>
    <fieldval field="hTotal" value="10"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="ShowCharge"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="Tools"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fListenCon" name="Listening Cone" description="This device is made for listening through doors and other solid surfaces. It provides a +2 circumstance bonus on Listen checks made through a door or some other relatively thin, solid obstacle.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="20"/>
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="1"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="Tools"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fThiefTLon" name="Thieves&apos; tools, Longspoon" description="These specially modified thieves tools are mounted on long, thin handles, enabling the user to manipulate latches, tinker with locks, and probe traps from a position up to 5 feet away and well off to the side of the target device. A 1-inch diameter mirror mounted on a long handle gives the user a good view of the object being manipulated. Though some traps can inflict harm even at a distance, these tools make it possible for a wary rogue to avoid many common hazards, such as poison needles, spurting acid, and the like.\n\nUsing these tools is more time consuming and less accurate than taking the direct approach; longspoon tools add 2 rounds to the time required to make a Disable Device or Open Lock check, and impose a -2 penalty on any Disable Device or Open Lock check for which they are used.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="3"/>
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="80"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="Tools" name="Tools and Skill Kits" abbrev="Tools"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fThiefTLoM" name="Thieves&apos; tools, masterwork Longspoon" description="These specially modified thieves tools are mounted on long, thin handles, enabling the user to manipulate latches, tinker with locks, and probe traps from a position up to 5 feet away and well off to the side of the target device. A 1-inch diameter mirror mounted on a long handle gives the user a good view of the object being manipulated. Though some traps can inflict harm even at a distance, these tools make it possible for a wary rogue to avoid many common hazards, such as poison needles, spurting acid, and the like.\n\nUsing these tools is more time consuming and less accurate than taking the direct approach. Masterwork longspoon tools still add 2 rounds to the time required to make a Disable Device or Open Lock check, but their +2 circumstance bonus cancels the normal -2 penalty on any Disable Device or Open Lock check for which they are used.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="3"/>
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="150"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="Tools" name="Tools and Skill Kits" abbrev="Tools"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fSadMilMwk" name="Saddle (Military), masterwork" description="This well made piece of gear is more comfortable and more responsive than a normal saddle. Because of its excellent craftsmanship, a masterwork saddle grants a +1 circumstance bonus on Ride checks. This bonus stacks with the normal +2 circumstance bonus a military saddle provides to ride checks relating to staying in the saddle.\n\nIf you&apos;re knocked unconscious while in a masterwork military saddle, you have a 75% chance to stay in the saddle (compared to 50% for a riding saddle).\n\nEach masterwork saddle is tailored for a specific kind of creature. As such, it fits best on that kind of creature and only provides its bonus while worn on that type of creature.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="40"/>
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="210"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="Mounts" name="Mounts and Related Gear" abbrev="Mounts"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fSadRidMwk" name="Saddle (Riding), masterwork" description="This well made piece of gear is more comfortable and more responsive than a normal saddle. Because of its excellent craftsmanship, a masterwork saddle grants a +1 circumstance bonus on Ride checks. \n\nIf you&apos;re knocked unconscious while in a masterwork riding saddle, you have a 50% chance to stay in the saddle.\n\nEach masterwork saddle is tailored for a specific kind of creature. As such, it fits best on that kind of creature and only provides its bonus while worn on that type of creature.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="30"/>
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="180"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="Mounts" name="Mounts and Related Gear" abbrev="Mounts"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize" name="GearNoSize" abbrev="GearNoSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fMusDrumM" name="Musical instrument, Drum mwk" description="A typical drum consists of skin, parchment, or some similar material stretched tightly over the opening of a hollow wooden cylinder or pot. This covered oeping is called the drumhead. Striking the drumhead with sticks, mallets, or even hands produces the sound. Some drums have only one drumhead; others have two or more. Drums exist in large varieties (such as kettle drums) as well as smaller varieties (such as bongo droms or the double ended tabor).\n\nDrums are popular with almost every race and culture for their ability to stir the emotions, establish a background beat for dancing, and provide counterpoint for a melody produced by some other instruments. Dwarves, orcs, and other races that favor underground living particularly enjoy the echoing power of drums. Smaller races, such as goblins and halflings, like bongo drums for their portability. The rare creatures that do not appreciate drum-playing include celestials, who consider drum rhythms primitive, and elves, who find them vaguely disturbing and annoying (a prejudice reinforced perhaps by the enthusiasm with which many of their enemies embrace them).\n\n{i}Bardic Music{/i}: When a bard uses a masterwork drum to inspire courage, the morale bonus on weapon damage rolls increases by 1, but the morale bonus on saves against charm and fear is reduced by 1.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="3"/>
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="100"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="Tools" name="Tools and Skill Kits" abbrev="Tools"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearSize" name="GearSize" abbrev="GearSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fMusFidleM" name="Musical instrument, Fiddle mwk" description="An ancestor of the modern violin, the fiddle is a small, portable stringed instrument with a body shaped rather like an hourglass. Four or five strings made of gut or sinew stretch across the body, anchored by pegs at the end of a long, thin neck. The strings are played with a seperate piece called the bow-a long, thin piece of wood strung with fine strands of animal hair. Fiddles vary in length from 2 feet (for medium fiddlers) and 18 inches (for halfling and kobold fiddlers). To play a fiddle, the musician holds it horizontally, typically with the base tucked under his chin, and draws the bow back and forth across the strings.\n\nThe fiddle is popular among bards who prefer lively dance music (reels and jigs) over serene but detatched &quot;pure&quot; music. Though welcome almost anywhere, the fiddle is the favored instrument of kobolds, whose clever hands mastered its fingerings ages ago. (They insist that they invented the fiddle, but other races find that claim dubious). Kobold minstrels and halfling bards typically caper about while playing, setting their audiance an example of the lively dancing their music encourages. Musicians of other races usually sit or stand to play the instrument.\n\n{i}Bardic Music{/i}: When a bard uses a masterwork fiddle to inspire courage, the morale bonus on saves against charm and fear increases by 1. In the hands of a bard with 5 or more ranks in Perform (dace), the morale bonus instead increases by 2.\n\nA bard who uses a fiddle for bardic music can cast spells while performing, but only if those spells have no somatic, material, or focus components.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="3"/>
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="100"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="Tools" name="Tools and Skill Kits" abbrev="Tools"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearSize" name="GearSize" abbrev="GearSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fMusFluteM" name="Musical instrument, Flute mwk" description="The flute is the highest pitched of all the woodwinds. This broad catagory includes instruments ranging from the primitive recorder flute - a simple, hollow tube that produces music when air is blown straight through it - to the traditional flute, which is held at a right angle to the musician&apos;s mouth.\n\nFlutes range in length from 8 inches to about 2 feet. The instrument has six holes (typically), plus a thumbhole that, when covered, lowers each of the other notes by an octave.\n\nFlutes have a reputation for producing a gentle, idyllic music, but they can also create more martial effects or distorted wailing sounds. Abyssal flutes always have an odd number of finger holes, and they conform to no scale or key used by humanoid bards. Particulasrly in the hands of demon pipers, they produce &quot;music&quot; that sounds to mortal ears like a disharmonius combination of sharps, flats, and bizarre, minor-key effects.\n\n{i}Bardic Music{/i}: A bard playing a masterwork flute gains a +2 bonus on Perform checks made to use the countersong ability.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="3"/>
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="100"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="Tools" name="Tools and Skill Kits" abbrev="Tools"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearSize" name="GearSize" abbrev="GearSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fMusHarpM" name="Musical instrument, Harp mwk" description="A harp typically has seventeen strings but can come with as few as twelve on a smaller instrument or as many as forty-seven on a larger one. Silver wires are the most common choice for strings, but other materials are occasionally used. Harps are usually made from wood, though some artisans carve them from bone or ivory. Whatever their material, most harps are highly polished and elaborately decorated with carvings. The finest rank as works of art in their own right, quite apart from their status as instruments. Though harps can stand up to 6 feet tall, portable versions (sometimes called lap-harps) are much smaller - about 2 feet high.\n\nThe harp is especially favored by elven bards for its light, soothing sound and gentle, rippling notes. Harps are often handed down from generation to generation among the elves, and many actually acquire names and legends of their own. Any character with the bardic knowledge ability who examines an elven harp automatically gains a +5 bonus on his or her bardic knowledge check to identify the instrument and its bearer\n\n{i}Bardic Music{/i}: A bard playing a masterwork harp can target one more creature than normal with her {i}fascinate{/i} and inspire greatness abilities.\n\nA bard who uses a harp for bardic music can cast spells while performing, but only if those spells have no somatic, material, or focus components.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="3"/>
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="100"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="Tools" name="Tools and Skill Kits" abbrev="Tools"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearSize" name="GearSize" abbrev="GearSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fMusHornM" name="Musical instrument, Horn mwk" description="Originally horns were, as their name suggests, actual horns taken from bulls or more exotic beasts. At its simplest, a horn consists of a narrow tip connected to a wider, circular orifice by a hollow, often curved shaft. A musician plays the horn by simply blowing into the small end. Other forms of horns exist, from the conch shell horn employed by merfolk to the herald&apos;s trumpet, but all these instruments function more or less identically.\n\nHorns are popular in primitive societies of all kinds. They come in all sizes; those used by medium creatures are typically 1 to 2 feet in length. Hobgoblins and orcs in particular enjoy these instruments for their loud, stirring, martial sound. Larger humanoids and giants favor horns made from dire creatures. Legend holds that minotaurs use instruments made from the severed horns of other minotaurs that suffered defeat in one-on-one contests of honor.\n\nA horn makes an excellent signal device - particularly when used underwater, since sound travels much farther in water than in air. Some aquatic races such as merfolk and kuo-toa collect a variety of horn shaped shells in different sizes and play them in harmony, in sequence, or both. The music of these seashell orchestras can achieve a deep, haunting grandeur.\n\n{i}Bardic Music{/i}: When a bard uses a masterwork horn to inspire courage, the morale bonus on weapon damage rolls and saves against fear increases by 1, but the effect lasts for only 1 round after the ally stops hearing the bard perform.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="3"/>
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="100"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="Tools" name="Tools and Skill Kits" abbrev="Tools"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearSize" name="GearSize" abbrev="GearSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fMusLuteM" name="Musical instrument, Lute mwk" description="This ancestor of the guitar has a pear-shaped bowl and a distinctive bent neck with frets for fingering. Between four and eight strings stretch between the base of the bowl and the top of the neck. Lutes vary between 30 and 36 inches in length, with the bowl taking up some two-thirds of that total. The musician either strums or plucks the strings to produce music.\n\nA highly versatile instrument because of its wide range of notes and inflection, the lute is accessible to the beginner but capable of great subtlety in the hands of a master. The deep bowl gives it a rich, full sound unlike that of any other stringed instrument. It is by far the most popular instrument with bards, especially the half-elf and human ones.\n\n{i}Bardic Music{/i}: A bard playing a masterwork lute is treated as one level higher for the purpose of adjucating the power of his bardic music effects. For example, a 3rd level bard using a masterwork lute could {i}fascinate{/i} two creatures instead of one, a 6th level bard making a {i}suggestion{/i} would calculate the save DC as though he were 7th level, and a 7th level bard inspiring courage would grant a +2 morale bonus on the appropriate rolls.\n\nA bard who uses a lute for bardic music can cast spells while performing, but only if those spells have no somatic, material, or focus components.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="3"/>
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="100"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="Tools" name="Tools and Skill Kits" abbrev="Tools"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearSize" name="GearSize" abbrev="GearSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fMusLyreM" name="Musical instrument, Lyre mwk" description="A simpler ancestor of the lap-harp, a lyre typically has a body made out of a turtle shell, plus two curved arms and a crossbar to hold its four to six (or, more rarely, eight) gut or sinew strings taut. To play a lyre, the musician holds it in one hand while strumming or plucking the strings with the other.\n\nThe very simplicity of the lyre is its charm, since even a novice can strum one to credible effect. Because of this accessability and the fact that they&apos;re easy to make, lyres are popular among the sylvan fey (especially satyrs) and country folk in general. On occasion, however, a true master adopts it as a signature instrument, producing astonishing effects.\n\n{i}Bardic Music{/i}: A bard playing a masterwork lyre can target one more creature than normal with her {i}fascinate{/i} and inspire heroics abilities.\n\nA bard who uses a lyre for bardic music can cast spells while performing, but only if those spells have no somatic, material, or focus components.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="3"/>
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="100"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="Tools" name="Tools and Skill Kits" abbrev="Tools"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearSize" name="GearSize" abbrev="GearSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fMusMandoM" name="Musical instrument, Mandolin mwk" description="Essentially a smaller version of the lute, a mandolin is usually between 20 inches and 2 feet long. It has a straighter neck than the lute - the end at which the pegs secure the strings tilts back only slightly, if at all. The mandolin is unusual for the number of strings it holds - from four to six pairs (eight to twelve strings total) or even more. A mandolin is typically played with a pick, both to protect the musician&apos;s fingers and becaus the strings are too close together to pluck accurately by hand.\n\nThe mandolin has a sweeter sound than the lute and, because of its shorter strings, a higher pitch as well. Its greater range of tone and expression have made it a favorite of gnomes and halflings, who champion it as superior even to the lute.\n\n{i}Bardic Music{/i}: When a bard uses a masterwork mandolin to inspire courage, the morale bonus on attack rolls increases by one, but the morale bonus on damage rolls and saves against charm and fear are reduced by one.\n\nA bard who uses a mandolin for bardic music can cast spells while performing, but only if those spells have no somatic, material, or focus components.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="3"/>
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="100"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="Tools" name="Tools and Skill Kits" abbrev="Tools"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearSize" name="GearSize" abbrev="GearSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fMusPanPM" name="Musical instrument, Pan Pipes mwk" description="In essence, a set of pan pipes is a series of hollow reeds or wooden tubes bound together in a row, from smallest to largest. To play them, the musician blows across the tops of the tubes, producing a sound much like that of several tiny wooden flutes. By moving the pipes from side to side, the the piper can play different notes. Switching rapidly among notes creates the sweet, rippling effect for which the instrument is known.\n\nSimple yet evocative, pan pipes are favorites of satyrs and other sylvan fey. Humans and some elves also find their music pleasing.\n\n{i}Bardic Music{/i}: A bard using masterwork pan pipes gains a +1 bonus on Perform checks made to {i}fascinate{/i} creatures, and also adds 1 to the save DC against the bard&apos;s {i}suggestion{/i} bardic music ability.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="3"/>
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="100"/>
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="Tools" name="Tools and Skill Kits" abbrev="Tools"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearSize" name="GearSize" abbrev="GearSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cNinja" name="Ninja" description="Ninjas move through the shadows, striking down the unwary and vanishing again with ease. Ninjas walk where others cannot. They blend their training in stealth and assassination with a focused mind. Their rigorous preparation sharpens their minds and bodies, giving them supernatural abilities of stealth and making them phantoms in the eyes of many. Although ninjas in battle lack the staying power of martial characters such as fighters or barbarians, they excel at making combat occur on their terms&#151;appearing and disappearing seemingly at a whim. \n\nHistorically, ninjas came from clans of assassins and guerrilla warriors in feudal Japan. In a fantasy setting, they blend a gift for stealth and infiltration with devastating surprise attacks and supernatural means of avoiding blows. Although the specific abilities of the class differ from those attributed to the historical ninja, they mirror the ninja&#146;s fearsome reputation as a spy, assassin, and martial artist.\n\n{b}Adventures{/b}: Ninjas adventure for a variety of reasons. A loyal ninja might adventure at her lord&#146;s command, using her abilities of stealth and subterfuge to ferret out his enemies or recover powerful treasures to be used in his service. A mercenary ninja might seek only treasure and fame, while a more idealistic ninja might seek to thwart a growing evil. Most ninjas prefer anonymity to fame, and they go out of their way to disguise their profession and abilities. A rare few, however, revel in the mysterious reputation that surrounds ninjas and their training, making known their abilities and their role in a famous adventuring group. As ninjas grow in wealth and power, their goals often change, and their ability to uncover secrets and kill stealthily can shape the plans of entire nations. Rulers both fear and covet the skills of the ninja, and high-level ninjas whose identities are known often find adventures coming to them rather than the converse.\n\n{b}Characteristics{/b}: Highly skilled spies and assassins, ninjas can master a broad range of skills and combat techniques. Nearly every ninja perfects the arts of moving quietly and remaining hidden, and her secondary skills define her role in an adventuring party or a community. Many ninjas hone skills that help them become better spies, mastering the arts of social interaction and disguise. Others take on the role of cat burglars, practicing skills that help them find and bypass traps and locks. \n\nIn combat, a ninja can deal out devastating blows if her opponent doesn&#146;t know she&#146;s there, but she&#146;s not quite as adept as a rogue is at delivering such attacks in a prolonged battle.\n\nNinjas jump and climb farther and faster than members of most other classes, and they are skilled acrobats as well. Ninjas also receive special training in the use of poisons, and many ninjas employ poisonous weapons in combat.\n\nEven with these impressive skills, a ninja&#146;s most dangerous and remarkable powers involve the ability to step briefly into the Ethereal Plane. By focusing her {i}ki{/i}, a ninja can vanish from sight, walk through solid walls, and deal devastating attacks even when not physically present at the scene. As a ninja advances in level, she can turn this ability to defense, causing blows that would otherwise hit to pass harmlessly through her body.\n\n{b}Alignment{/b}: Although ninjas have a reputation as dangerous assassins and deceptive spies, they follow many different philosophies and ideals and can be of any alignment. For every dangerous mercenary who uses her ninja training to kill for money, an honest and loyal ninja stands guard over a just lord. Most ninjas follow their own beliefs rather than the dictates of a noble or magistrate, and therefore more ninjas are chaotic than lawful.\n\n{b}Religion{/b}: A ninja&#146;s religious beliefs follow those of her clan. In a fantasy game, ninjas can follow any god, although most clans devote themselves to deities of stealth or trickery. Neutral or mercenary ninjas might devote themselves to Olidammara (the god of thieves). Evil ninjas might revere Nerull (the god of death) or Erythnul (the god of slaughter).\n\nNinjas who have left or lost their clan follow any deity and often choose not to worship a deity.\n\n{b}Background{/b}: Many ninjas come from isolated clans that train in secret. They spend years perfecting the arts of stealth and subterfuge in distant villages and hidden training camps. These warriors, whether deployed in the service of an honorable lord or sent to serve as mercenary assassins, carefully conceal their identities and origins. These ninjas weave complicated webs of disguises, strike only from hiding, and deal through intermediaries whenever possible. Because of their strong ties to their clan, these ninjas must often put aside personal preferences or goals to serve their lord or clan, but in return they gain the support of a powerful political force and access to the clan&#146;s many safe houses and hideouts.\n\nAlthough most ninjas come from such isolated clans, exceptions exist at every turn. Some ninjas receive specialized training from a single mentor, perhaps even a retired adventurer who wishes to pass along his skills. Others train alongside monks and other ascetics in a peaceful monastery. In some places, far-thinking nobles set up their own ninja training centers. One of these centers might consist merely of a single teacher with a handful of students; another might be a full-blown ninja school that progresses students through a rigid series of tests, ranks, and trials.\n\n{b}Races{/b}: Humans, halflings, half-elves, and half-orcs often have the combination of adaptability and ambition necessary to master the techniques of the ninja. Elves, both graceful and deadly, rarely become ninjas, but those who do often achieve great fame or notoriety. Such elf ninjas often attain the heights of ninja prowess, shaping the history of many human generations through their daring exploits. Dwarves and gnomes seldom train as ninjas. Not only is their social structure too open to shelter hidden clans of ninjas, but their martial instincts run to more straightforward forms of combat.\n\n{b}Other Classes{/b}: Ninjas work best with rogues, scouts, or rangers. Although they appreciate the healing power of clerics and the sheer offensive might of fighters and barbarians, ninjas rely too much on stealth to completely embrace the idea of adventuring with other classes. Conversely, when traveling or not actively adventuring, ninjas who wish to go unnoticed benefit greatly from the presence of other classes. The less subtle and more visible her adventuring companions are, the easier it is for a ninja to remain in the background and disguise her own abilities.\n\n{b}Role{/b}: Depending on a ninja&#146;s skill selection and the mission that her party undertakes, the character&#146;s role in the group can vary dramatically. A ninja practiced in disguise and diplomacy might assume a false identity and act as the group&#146;s leader and front person. A stealthy ninja who has perfected the arts of infiltration might act as a scout or point, while a more cautious ninja might hang back, covering the group&#146;s rear. Whatever a ninja&#146;s role during routine dungeon exploration or other adventures, she is a dangerous and unpredictable combatant who can disable foes with poison, seemingly strike from nowhere, and escape almost any situation by using her supernatural abilities.\n\n{b}Source{/b}: Complete Adventurer" compset="ClassLevel" maxlimit="20">
    <usesource source="CompAdvent"/>
